{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1.**\n\nThis work addresses the cutting of a Brahmin's top-knot (*śikhā*) in several scenarios. For a **single cutting by an enemy**, one should \"wear hair from a cow's tail on his ear and, being pure, should perform a Prājāpatya penance,\" followed by a new *saṃskāra* for full purity.[^1] For **cutting in the middle**, \"he is purified by a Prājāpatya penance.\"[^2]\n\nFor **five cuttings by enemies**, however: \"By any means whatsoever, one should wear the top-knot and the sacred thread. If the top-knot is cut by enemies five times, his Brahminhood is lost, even with a new *saṃskāra*.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-94f7a6).\n\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-6dc072).\n\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-f210ca).",
